                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d424">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">852.75 National Telephone Company/35:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Spain (<persName type="from"
                            >Laughlin</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Madrid</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-11-18T15:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 18, 1932—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>86. Bill of December 10, 1931 for annulation of telephone contract has been
                    resuscitated. Company has been cited to appear before Communications Committee
                    of Cortes this afternoon to show cause why “illegal” contract should not be
                    abrogated. Interpellations directed against company are likewise expected.
                        <persName corresp="#p_AM1">Azaña</persName> does not appear to be
                    antagonistic but he has made it clear to <persName corresp="#p_RCLN1"
                        >Rock</persName> that position of Government is too delicate to enable him
                    at present to afford much parliamentary protection. The outlook for the company
                    is serious.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
